replies.comment info:
@big kemp Nice interpretation of the information shown in the graph. Does this concern you? Do you think it's showing any trends that might continue? 
What are your questions?
What about your title?

@Gage Klinker
Thanks for commenting! I wonder if high school students are more likely to begin using e-cigarettes (and other forms of tobacco) because they are more likely to work (and have money) than middle school students. Personally, it is mind boggling that students would rather spend their hard earned money on something that is harmful to their bodies than on something else they may want, like to save for their first car. 

Why do you think the usage of e-cigarettes has been rising so quickly?

@Carmen F.
You are very well spoken!  I agree that this has become quite an epidemic. It amazes me that students choose to spend their money that they work so hard for on e-cigarettes and other tobacco products. It is much harder to save for something important, like your first car, when spending a ton of money on tobacco products. 

Do you think this trend will continue into the future or do you think that this will fade over time?

@Logan
Hi Logan! I agree that this is becoming quite a problem. I wonder if educating students at a young age about the danger of tobacco use (particularly e-cigarettes) would help?  I would suspect that young students, maybe in grade 6 would be more receptive to considering the down side to picking up a habit like tobacco usage. Besides the health risks, I wonder if pointing out the fact that it is expensive would make a difference?  Studies have shown that those who use tobacco tend to be poorer than those who do not. Maybe students would be less likely to use tobacco if they were presented with other healthy alternatives.

What do you think?

@Justin Tims
Hi Justin!  One thing to note is that the E-cigarettes is a subset of "any tobacco product" usage. From this we can see the percentage of students that use E-cigarettes and the percentage of students that use any tobacco product at all (including E-cigarettes). So it seems that about 30% of high school students use some form of tobacco. 

In your experience, does it seem that the estimate should be greater than that? Do you think that 50% of high school students use tobacco products?

@G.McBride
Nice noticing and wondering!  I wonder if the percentage of students that smoke traditional cigarettes is declining due to the increase in the usage of E-cigarettes? The closer that the E-cigarettes trend approaches the "any tobacco product" trend line, the fewer and fewer students there are using other tobacco products, like traditional cigarettes. 

Do you think that cigarettes will be a thing of the past at some point due to the rise of E-cigarettes?  What do you think the graph would look like if this were to happen?

@Zoe
Hi Zoe! You bring up an interesting point about the numbers seeming low. Data collection methods are so important for obtaining accurate estimates, like the percentage of middle and high school students that use tobacco or more specifically E-cigarettes. 

I wonder how these data were collected?  Maybe the original article, when it is released, will reveal the answer.  I imagine that many students would not admit to using E-cigarettes or other tobacco products if they were asked by a teacher or administrator. So I wonder how the CDC determines these figures.

@Aliana 
Nice noticing and wondering! Remember, that E-cigarettes are a subset of "any tobacco product", so when the E-cigarette trend lines approach that of "any tobacco product" that means that a smaller percentage of students are using other tobacco products and a greater percentage of students are choosing E-cigarettes  over traditional cigarettes and other tobacco products.

What do you think the trend will be in the next few years?

@Jamie W 
That is interesting that you find these numbers to be low. The methods of the data collection are always an important consideration when interpreting data. Imagine, for example, if these data were collected by an administrator asking students face to face about their tobacco usage. In such a case, we would expect the percentage to underestimate the true percentage of students that use tobacco. 

Check back later and read the original article to see if there may be some answers regarding how these data were collected.

@amani
Interesting noticing and wondering!  With E-cigarettes being more than halfway to "any tobacco product" it seems that over 50% of tobacco users are now using E-cigarettes. Compared to 2011, that is a very big change.

What do you think the trend will be in the next few years?

@Zack S
I also see the big jump in the percentage of high school students using tobacco products and E-cigarettes. The change in percentage from 2017 to 2018 is shocking. 

I wonder why there was a decrease in percentage from 2016 to 2017 prior to this sharp recent increase?  Any ideas?

@Austin L
Love your headline, Austin!  One important thing to note is that E-cigarettes are included among the "Any tobacco product" trend lines. This means that you can determine the percentage of students using tobacco products other than E-cigarettes by subtracting, or finding the vertical distance between the two lines for any particular time. 

I wonder if the rising popularity of E-cigarettes will cause the usage of other tobacco products, like traditional cigarettes, to decline?  What do you think?

@Olivia C
Hi Olivia! Thanks for noticing and wondering so many things about this graph. Juul is a type of E-cigarrete, just like "Kleenex" is type of facial tissue, so Juul is included in the graph in the E-cigarettes category. 

What do you think is driving the sudden popularity of E-cigarettes, like Juul?
